Author-Name: Richard Sylla 
Author-Name: Jack Wilson 
Author-Name: Robert Wright 
Title: Integration of Trans-Atlantic Capital Markets, 1790-1845 
Abstract:
		       During the 1790s, European investors began to
 purchase substantial quantities of US government and corporate securities.
 A number of these securities were traded in markets on both sides of the
 Atlantic. Based on market price quotations we compiled for the same
 securities in London and New York markets, we ask if these early
 trans-Atlantic securities markets were integrated, and, if so, when they
 became integrated. We find little evidence of market integration before
 1816, and substantial evidence of it thereafter. Financial globalization -
 the convergence of financial asset prices in markets on different
 continents - began earlier than most have suspected.			 Copyright Oxford University Press Science+Business Media, LLC 2006
