Author-Name:  Alfred Lehar 
Author-Name:  Otto Randl 
Title: Chinese Walls in German Banks 
Abstract:
 Analysts in a bank's research department cover firms that have no
 relationship with the bank as well as companies in which the bank has a
 strategic interest. Officially, banks must establish Chinese Walls around
 their research departments to allow the analysts to work independently and
 to avoid the flow of insider information. We examine analyst behavior
 under long-term bank-firm relationships using ownership data and analysts'
 earnings per share forecasts for German companies from 1994 to 2001. We
 find evidence that is consistent with analysts reconciling their
 employers' interests with their own career concerns. They seem to use
 their information advantage strategically by releasing favorable and
 thereby more precise reports when the market underestimates earnings. In
 order not to jeopardize the bank-client relationship, they suppress
 negative information when the market is too optimistic. Combining
 situations where the market over- and underestimates earnings, we can
 replicate the unconditional positive bias in analyst forecasts found in
 the previous literature. Despite the bias in affiliated analysts'
 forecasts, they nonetheless selectively communicate valuable information
 to investors. Copyright 2006, Oxford University Press.
