Author-Name:  Daniella Acker
Author-Name:  Nigel W. Duck 
Title: Do Investors Suffer from Money Illusion? A Direct Test of the Modigliani--Cohn Hypothesis 
Abstract:
 We propose a direct test of the explanation by Modigliani and Cohn (MC)
 for the positive correlation between inflation and equity values--that it
 results from investors' money illusion. This explanation, unlike its main
 rivals, suggests that because in inflationary periods dividends will, on
 average, be higher than expected, dividend announcements will trigger
 positive abnormal returns. These will be higher the higher the inflation,
 and the more levered the firm. The behavior of abnormal returns of US
 stocks on dividend-announcement days from 1955 to 2007 supports these
 predictions. We investigate alternative explanations of our results. None
 dominates MC's. Copyright 2013, Oxford University Press.
