Author-Name:  Assaf Hamdani
Author-Name:  Yishay Yafeh 
Title: Institutional Investors as Minority Shareholders 
Abstract:
 We examine the link between minority shareholders' rights and corporate
 governance by studying institutional investors' voting patterns in a
 concentrated ownership environment. Institutions rarely vote against
 insider-sponsored proposals even when the law empowers the minority.
 Institutions vote against compensation-related proposals more often than
 against related party transactions even when minority shareholders cannot
 influence outcomes. Potentially conflicted institutions are more likely to
 vote for insiders' proposals than stand-alone investors, regardless of
 their effect on outcomes. A plausible conclusion is that empowering
 minority shareholders affects the selection of proposals but not actual
 voting; another is that empowering minority shareholders is ineffective
 without addressing conflicts of interest. Copyright 2013, Oxford University Press.
