Title: Structuring the Initial Offering: Who to Sell To and How to Do It 
Abstract:
		       We develop a unified model of the issuer’s decisions
 that takes into account both mechanism design and adverse selection risk.
 The model enables us to determine the optimal amount of information
 gathering prior to setting the offer price, and to understand what does
 and does not cause underpricing. The flexibility to allocate securities
 between a pool of investors who provide pricingrelevant information and
 investors who do not provide information is key to controlling
 underpricing. Policies that guarantee a minimum allocation to investors in
 the pool result in underpricing; policies that cap the allocations to such
 investors do not. The optimal number of investors in the pool, and thus
 the amount of information acquired, generally increases with the riskiness
 of the issue. However, this relation breaks down if pool members are
 guaranteed minimum allocations.		    Copyright Oxford University Press 2006
