Author-Name:  John Morgan 
Title: Securities Auctions under Moral Hazard: An Experimental Study 
Abstract:
 In many settings, including venture capital financing, mergers and
 acquisitions, and lease competition, the structure of the contracts over
 which firms compete differs. Furthermore, the structure of the contract
 affects the future incentives of the firm to engage in value-creating
 activities by potentially diluting effort or investment incentives. We
 study, both theoretically and in the lab, the performance of debt and
 equity auctions in the presence of both private information and hidden
 effort. We show that the revenues to sellers in debt and equity auctions
 differ systematically depending on the returns to entrepreneurial effort.
 Using a controlled laboratory experiments we test the model's predictions
 and find strong support for the theory. Copyright 2010, Oxford University Press.
