Author-Name:  Hazem Daouk 
Title: When No Law is Better Than a Good Law 
Abstract:
 This paper argues, both theoretically and empirically, that sometimes no
 securities law may be better than a good securities law that is not
 enforced. The first part of the paper formalizes the sufficient conditions
 under which this happens for any law. The second part of the paper shows
 that a specific securities law -- the law prohibiting insider trading --
 may satisfy these conditions. The third part of the paper takes this
 prediction to the data. We find that the cost of equity actually rises
 when some countries enact an insider trading law, but do not enforce it. Copyright 2009, Oxford University Press.
