Author-Name:  Radhakrishnan Gopalan
Author-Name:  Todd A. Gormley 
Title: Do Public Equity Markets Matter in Emerging Economies? Evidence from India 
Abstract:
 Do public equity markets serve an unique role that is not easily served by
 other forms of financing in emerging economies? We analyze this question
 using the collapse of India's equity market in 1997, which provides an
 exogenous shock to firms' ability to issue equity. We find that both
 public and private firms exhibit higher bankruptcy rates and lower growth
 after 1997. The decline in growth is greater among firms with more
 external finance needs and fewer tangible assets. Overall, the evidence
 suggests that public equity markets are an important, not easily replaced,
 source of finance in emerging economies. Copyright 2013, Oxford University Press.
