Author-Name:  Tse-Chun Lin 
Author-Name:  Otto Van Hemert 
Title: How the 52-Week High and Low Affect Option-Implied Volatilities and Stock Return Moments 
Abstract:
 We provide a new perspective on option and stock price behavior around
 52-week highs and lows. We analyze whether option-implied volatilities
 (IVs) change when stock prices approach or break through their 52-week
 high or low. We also study the effects of highs and lows on a stock's beta
 and return volatility. We find that IVs and stock betas decrease when
 approaching a high or low, and that volatilities increase after
 breakthroughs. The effects are economically large and significant. The
 approach results can be explained by the anchoring theory. The
 breakthrough results are consistent with anchoring and the investor
 attention hypothesis. Copyright 2013, Oxford University Press.
