Author-Name:  Ernst Maug 
Author-Name:  Christoph Schneider 
Title: Bankers on the Boards of German Firms: What They Do, What They Are Worth, and Why They Are (Still) There 
Abstract:
 We analyze the role of bankers on the boards of German non-financial
 companies for the period from 1994 to 2005. We find that banks that are
 represented on a firm's board promote their own business as lenders and as
 M&A advisors. They also seem to act as financial experts who help firms to
 obtain funding, especially in difficult times. We find little evidence
 that bankers monitor management and suggest that bankers on the board
 cause a decline in the valuations of non-financial firms. Banks' equity
 ownership declined sharply during our sample period and the German
 financial system lost some of its formerly distinctive features. Copyright 2010, Oxford University Press.
