Author-Name:  Yawen Jiao
Title: Hedge Funds and Equity Prices 
Abstract:
 This article analyzes hedge funds' expansion during 2000--09 and its
 implications for stock returns. Hedge funds more than doubled their equity
 ownership prior to the 2007--09 financial crisis. In this expansion
 period, their trading predicts increasing one-quarter-ahead stock returns
 and return reversals in the 2nd year. These reversals stem from the
 expansion of mature funds, while young funds' trading predicts
 one-quarter-ahead returns without future reversals. The above price
 pressures disappear when hedge funds shift to contractions in the
 financial crisis. These findings are consistent with mature funds'
 expansions exerting pressures on equities and young funds possessing stock
 picking skills. Copyright 2013, Oxford University Press.
