Author-Name:  Elisabeth Mueller 
Title: Returns to Private Equity - Idiosyncratic Risk Does Matter! 
Abstract:
 Owners of private companies often invest a substantial share of their net
 worth in one company, which exposes them to idiosyncratic risk. We
 investigate whether owners of US companies require compensation for lack
 of diversification in the form of higher returns on equity. Exposure to
 idiosyncratic risk is measured as the share of the owner's net worth
 invested in the company. Equity returns are measured as the earnings rate
 and as capital gains. For both returns measures we find a positive and
 significant influence of exposure to idiosyncratic risk. This paper
 improves our understanding of returns on private equity. Copyright 2010, Oxford University Press.
