Title: Fund Liquidation, Self-selection, and Look-ahead Bias in the Hedge Fund Industry 
Abstract:
 A wide range of empirical biases hampers hedge fund databases. In this
 paper we focus upon survival-related biases and disentangle look-ahead
 biases due to self-selection of funds and due to fund termination.
 Self-selection arises because funds voluntarily report their information
 to data vendors and may decide to stop doing so. By extending existing
 methodology, we analyze persistence in hedge fund performance over the
 period 1994-2000, taking into account the above biases. The results show
 that look-ahead biases due to liquidation and self-selection enforce each
 other and may lead to overestimating expected returns by as much as 8% per
 year. Overall, the results are consistent with positive persistence in
 hedge fund returns at horizons of two and four quarters. Copyright 2007, Oxford University Press.
