Title: Informed Finance and Technological Conservatism 
Abstract:
 This paper studies an economy in which firms can operate either a mature
 or a new technology and lenders acquire information on the productive
 assets of the borrowing firms that are eligible as collateral. We
 demonstrate that when contracts are imperfectly enforceable informed
 lenders offer inexpensive funding for the mature technology but may choose
 not to finance the new one, seeking to preserve the value of their
 information on the mature assets. Using firm-level data from Italy, we
 find that banks that establish long-term relationships with firms promote
 technological progress on average. However, we find that relationship
 banks inhibit innovations that entail a large depreciation of existing
 technology-specific information such as radical innovations. Copyright 2010, Oxford University Press.
