Title: Time Variation in Mutual Fund Style Exposures 
Abstract:
 Despite the wide acceptance of return-based style analysis, the method has
 several limitations. One important drawback is the assumption that style
 exposures are time-invariant. We apply results on break tests developed in
 Bai and Perron (1998, 2003) to test for style breaks. We find strong
 evidence against the hypothesis of constant time exposures in daily return
 data for European equity funds. All funds exhibit at least one break, and
 60% exhibit more than one break. We show that the main reason for style
 breaks is the mutual funds' reliance on conditional investment strategies
 based on public information and volatility estimates. Copyright 2007, Oxford University Press.
